s matter and the adoption of new fining guidelines by the European Data Pro=
tection Board. That, though, primarily serves to obscure the fact that cost=
s have been down and to the right all year, culminating in a net operating =
margin of 40% this quarter. Meta hasn=E2=80=99t hit those levels since the =
2021 COVID bubble, and late 2019 before that.

Reels Reaches Revenue Neutral
-----------------------------

Meanwhile, here is my usual Meta earnings chart:

The fact that Impressions growth slowed is the evidence of the claim made b=
y Meta executives on the earnings call ( https://s21.q4cdn.com/399680738/fi=
les/doc_earnings/2023/q3/transcript/META-Q3-2023-Earnings-Call-Transcript.p=
df ) that Reels is now revenue neutral; CFO Susan Li said in her prepared r=
emarks:

On Reels, we have continued to improve monetization and are now at a level =
where Reels is neutral to overall revenue. We=E2=80=99ve made tremendous pr=
ogress over the last year building and scaling Reels as a consumer product =
=E2=80=93 and it has now become part of the core experience on Instagram an=
d Facebook. As such, we don=E2=80=99t anticipate quantifying the net revenu=
e contribution from Reels going forward. We will still work to further impr=
ove Reels ads performance through ranking improvements and making Reels ads=
 increasingly interactive, while also growing supply to give businesses mor=
e opportunities to get in front of people. We anticipate this ongoing work =
will help Reels be a modest tailwind to revenue in 2024 while we continue t=
o strike the right balance between engagement and revenue growth. But our f=
ocus going forward will be on growing revenue and engagement on overall vid=
eo, and more holistically across our product lines within Instagram and Fac=
ebook.

Li does say that Meta will continue to increase Reels inventory, but my rea=
d of this statement and the attenuation in impressions growth is that a big=
 part of Reels monetization to date has been simply adding more ads to Reel=
s; now there is enough that the time spent on Reels =E2=80=94 and thus not =
spent on Stories or the Feed, which monetize very effectively =E2=80=94 is =
paid for by the monetization that happens in Reels. Future growth will come=
 from increasing the efficacy of Reels ads =E2=80=94 which Meta said is bei=
ng worked on =E2=80=94 and improvements in targeting, which are represented=
 by the improvement in price-per-ad.

Now the first order factor in price-per-ad has traditionally been the numbe=
r of impressions, which makes sense on an auction-based ad platform: if the=
re is more supply, then prices will be lower, and if there is less than pri=
ces will be higher. What has been so remarkable over the last few quarters,=
 though, is that impressions have grown even as the rate of decline in pric=
ing has decreased (and while impressions growth decreased this quarter, tha=
t only reduced the rate of decline in pricing even more sharply).

I have, to date, chalked this up to Meta figuring out how to do ad-targetin=
g again after Apple=E2=80=99s App Tracking Transparency broke their previou=
s system (and led to a sharper decline in prices-per-ad in 2022 than you wo=
uld expect from the increase in impressions). I do still think that plays a=
 role, but it=E2=80=99s fair to wonder if something else might be going on.=
 Specifically, why do Meta executives keep talking about China?

The Temu and Shein Effect
-------------------------

This is from Li=E2=80=99s prepared remarks:

Within ad revenue, the online commerce vertical was the largest contributor=
 to year-over-year growth, followed by CPG and gaming. Online commerce and =
gaming benefited from strong spend among advertisers in China reaching cust=
omers in other markets.

Li expounded on this revenue in the question-and-answer portion of the call=
:

So your first question, I think, was about regional trends or regional them=
es in our ad revenue, which as you saw this quarter accelerated across all =
regions. To give you a little bit of color, in North America, we saw accele=
rate by 7 points due primarily to strong demand from China advertisers. Not=
e that North America didn=E2=80=99t experience the same currency tailwinds =
that drove acceleration in year-over-year growth for the other regions.

In our EU region, we saw that accelerate 21 points. There was a broad-based=
 acceleration in the region, including demand from China advertisers and so=
me benefit from currency tailwinds after facing currency headwinds in Q2. A=
sia Pacific accelerated 9 points. We benefited from stronger demand in Sout=
heast Asian countries, and again, the flip to currency tailwinds versus hea=
dwinds in Q2. Rest of World accelerated 20 points. We saw both stronger pri=
cing and the same currency dynamic there. Brazil was a strong contributor t=
o the region=E2=80=99s acceleration due in part to increased demand from Ch=
ina advertisers targeting users in Brazil.

Li first mentioned this revenue in April=E2=80=99s Q1 earnings call ( https=
://seekingalpha.com/article/4597020-meta-platforms-inc-meta-q1-2023-earning=
s-call-transcript ) :

And in particular, we saw acceleration among advertisers in China targeting=
 users in other markets, which we believe was due, in part, to dropping shi=
pping costs and easing COVID lockdowns for those advertisers.

In last quarter=E2=80=99s earnings call ( https://seekingalpha.com/article/=
4620268-meta-platforms-inc-meta-q2-2023-earnings-call-transcript ) Li said:

Online commerce benefited from strong span among advertisers in China, reac=
hing customers in other markets.

I think the Q1 commentary threw me off the scent a little bit in the 2nd qu=
arter: this Chinese revenue isn=E2=80=99t (just) a COVID story; it=E2=80=99=
s a Temu and Shein story. From Reuters last month ( https://www.reuters.com=
/world/china/chinas-e-commerce-discount-race-bottom-puts-incumbents-under-p=
ressure-2023-09-26/ ) :

In much of the rest of the world, meanwhile, from Southeast Asia to North A=
merica and Europe, consumers are in the thrall of fast-growing platforms, l=
ike PDD Holdings=E2=80=99 Temu and Bytedance-owned TikTok Shop, which ship =
cheap goods from China at a time when cost-of-living is front of mind for m=
any. China has long been a major exporter of a host of consumer products, b=
ut this latest export trend, of its e-commerce marketplace dynamics to the =
rest of the world, has shaken up online shopping globally=E2=80=A6

Fast-rising discount competitors, such as Pinduoduo and Douyin in China and=
 Temu and Shein, which have rolled out their services to countries from Can=
ada to Australia, as well as across Latin America and some Asian markets, a=
re themselves pouring billions of dollars into subsidies and discounts to g=
row market share among consumers who are happier to snap up $10 dresses and=
 $5 headphones than higher-priced items.

Those subsidies and discounts aren=E2=80=99t just going to dresses and head=
phones: they are going to ads on Meta in particular, replaying the strategy=
 that TikTok leveraged to great effect to grow around the world. From Meta=
=E2=80=99s perspective, this inevitably has an impact on my favorite chart:=
 increased demand for Meta ads means higher prices. Moreover, to the extent=
 that Temu and Shein are subsidizing growth is the extent to which they are=
 probably not particularly concerned about their return-on-advertising-spen=
d (ROAS), which means they continue to buy even as the price of ads increas=
es because of their increased volume.

Moreover, the impact of Temu and Shein=E2=80=99s volume has even more far-r=
eaching impacts; on the follow-up earnings call ( https://s21.q4cdn.com/399=
680738/files/doc_earnings/2023/q3/transcript/META-Q3-2023-Follow-Up-Call-Tr=
anscript.pdf ) Li said in response to a question about Meta=E2=80=99s recov=
ery from ATT:

We certainly believe that advertising is a relevant performance game and th=
at we have made and continue to make improvements to our performance =E2=80=
=94 to the features available, to the performance and measurement of our ad=
 products in recent periods and we=E2=80=99ve received consistent positive =
feedback from advertisers on that. So, we feel good about our position rela=
tive to other options for advertisers in the market right now.

This is exactly right: Meta=E2=80=99s advertising is the best option availa=
ble, even if it costs more; the price that matters isn=E2=80=99t the top-li=
ne cost of an ad, but rather the aforementioned ROAS =E2=80=94 and remember=
 that you have to also consider the overhead of advertising across multiple=
 platforms instead of just sticking with Meta. Moreover, this latter advant=
age has only increased with the shift to probabilistic targeting, where the=
 best results come from trusting the platform to a much greater extent than=
 before.

The reason this matters in the context of these Chinese apps is that Temu a=
nd Shein=E2=80=99s volume is likely also causing other advertisers to pay m=
ore: sure, there are some marginal customers that are getting priced out, b=
ut the reality is that Meta probably has more latitude than ever in terms o=
f pricing. Again, I am not saying that Meta is raising prices =E2=80=94 Met=
a pricing is based on an auction, which means the price is set by the 2nd-h=
ighest bidder =E2=80=94=C2=A0but rather that Temu and Shein are likely serv=
ing as a stalking horse of sorts to increase prices for everyone, to Meta=
=E2=80=99s benefit.

Temu and Shein are not, to be clear, responsible for all of Meta=E2=80=99s =
growth; in a recent analysis MoffettNathanson ( https://www.moffettnathanso=
n.com/media-home ) put the two companies Meta spend at just under $3 billio=
n year-to-date; Meta=E2=80=99s revenue is up around $11 billion year-over-y=
ear in that same time period. Moreover, this spend is both more palatable a=
nd potentially sustainable than TikTok=E2=80=99s spend was: e-commerce apps=
 are not a strategic threat to Meta =E2=80=94 quite the opposite in fact =
=E2=80=94 and also lack network effects to make them self-sustaining entiti=
es like TikTok has become. Still, subsidies could go away, macro events cou=
ld intervene, etc.; Meta still deserves the credit for figuring out ATT, bu=
t Temu and Shein do make the story a bit more complicated.

